	"reading",
	"Nelson Mandela was born in 1918 in South Africa. He grew up during a time when black people faced severe discrimination under apartheid, a system that separated people by race. Despite these challenges, Mandela was determined to fight for equality and justice.\n\nWhile he was studying law at university, Mandela became involved in the anti-apartheid movement. He joined the African National Congress (ANC) and dedicated his life to ending racial discrimination. In 1964, he was arrested and sentenced to life in prison. He spent 27 years in jail, but he never gave up his beliefs.\n\nDuring his imprisonment, Mandela became a symbol of resistance. People around the world, which included leaders and ordinary citizens, campaigned for his release. Finally, in 1990, he was freed. Four years later, he became South Africa's first black president.\n\nMandela's legacy is remarkable. He showed that perseverance and forgiveness can overcome hatred. His story inspires millions of people to stand up for justice. He received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1993 and is remembered as one of the most influential leaders in history.",
