	"Mass media has such a powerful influence on society that it shapes public opinion and behavior. Social media platforms have grown so rapidly that billions of people now use them daily. Information spreads so quickly online that a news story can reach millions within minutes. However, this speed creates problems - fake news can go viral just as fast as accurate information.\n\nJournalists report news as if they are providing objective facts, but media bias exists everywhere. Some outlets present information in such a way that it supports their political views. The more sensational a headline, the more clicks it receives, so media companies sometimes prioritize attention over accuracy. Unless readers develop critical thinking skills, they may believe misinformation.\n\nDespite these challenges, mass media plays a vital role in democracy. If people have access to reliable information, they can make informed decisions. The key is media literacy - the ability to evaluate sources critically. As long as we question what we read and verify facts, we can benefit from mass media while avoiding its pitfalls.",
