	"reading3",
	"Wildlife conservation has become more urgent than ever. Many species are disappearing so quickly that scientists cannot study them in time. If we don't take immediate action, countless species will become extinct within our lifetime.\n\nThe main threats are habitat loss, poaching, and climate change. Deforestation destroys animal homes so extensively that entire ecosystems collapse. Tigers are more endangered now than 50 years ago because their habitats have shrunk dramatically. Unless we stop destroying forests, many species will disappear forever.\n\nPoaching remains a serious problem. Illegal hunters kill elephants for ivory and rhinos for horns. The demand for wildlife products is as high as it has ever been. If governments enforced stricter laws, fewer animals would be killed. Some countries have made progress - provided that anti-poaching patrols are well-funded, they can protect animals effectively.\n\nClimate change affects wildlife in ways that are not always obvious. As temperatures rise, animals must adapt or move. However, many species cannot move fast enough. The faster the climate changes, the harder it is for animals to survive. Despite these challenges, there are success stories. Giant pandas have recovered thanks to conservation efforts. This shows that if we invest in conservation, species can recover. The more people understand biodiversity's importance, the more support conservation receives. As long as we work together, there is hope for wildlife.",
